it? <BR>  <BR> I can see 2 schools of thought to this and both have merits and drawbacks: <BR> 1) Let whoever needs it loot it.  If more than one person needs it then use lotto.  In no one in the group needs it lotto for it and whoever gets it then can either use it to trade or offer it to another guild member… their choice. <BR>  <BR> 2)  lotto all items among the group no matter what the class.  This is what will most likely happen in a mixed (non-Claw) group as well.  This seems to cause the least disputes (no accusations of favoritism, etc.) but also leads to major group turnover.  Person X wins the loot they want… they leave… the party can’t hold the spawn and noone else gets a chance to loot.  This seems to happen ALL the time.  If you are in a claw group and can stick around AFTER you got what you wanted this is always the right thing to do. <BR>  <BR> In all cases, once you have looted a valuable item (whether to use, trade, or give away) you should refrain from rolling for the remainder of that hunt. <BR>  <BR> I tend toward option number 1 whenever I am grouping with people I have grouped with before.  Giving items among your friends and guildmates is basically like trading.  What goes around, comes around.  Hehe.  I “traded” gatorscale sleeves to Muirlan for a runed mith bracer (hehehe… he was ripped off but who’s keeping track?)  We didn’t exactly trade.  I gave him sleeves when I didn’t need them and a few weeks later he gave me a bracer he didn’t need.  I’m sure if either of us loots an item the other desires these kinds of trades will continue. <BR>  <BR> It worked for Sarivek (our newest zapper).  He was trying to trade an executioners hood for a nightshade wreath.  Noone in cazic or guk wanted to trade, so he gave the hood to Freyja.  The next day, Emeraldeyes and Sarivek and Zaya (sp?)(and later Aradan and I) camped the wreath.  Sarivek got his wreath.  Voila!  Yes both these examples are for fairly common items that you can buy with plat (rather than trade only) but I think the concept is valid. <BR>  <BR> Will this work for the REALLY expenxive/rare items?  I dunno.  Depends on the people in the guild and what we want to do.  Personally, I hope I find the generosity to still give things away.  Primary characters in the guild should come first.  My twink enchanter is wearing silk not an oracle robe.  Until EVERY caster in the guild has a nice robe that will be the case.  Primary chars come first in my philosophy.  Besides, by the time I’m 50 and playing my enchanter more, all the casters will have SMR and I’m sure I’ll get a good deal on an oracle robe.  Hehehe.  Rarely traded or auctioned, and never want to.  Never have more plat in the bank than I need for spells and supplies or buying things for friends.  Every piece of equipment I wear has either been looted, given to me, or crafted for me.  (Yes, Indiana twinked me with azure sleeves when I was 25 to so, but I count that as advance payment for all the ports I give him!) <BR>  <BR> I think it will work within the Claw for one main reason:  we need each other.  I’ll camp all night in MM to help Aradan get a drum because there is NO WAY I will ever loot a brown chitin protector without his (or other claws) help.  Sure I could roll against him hoping to trade a bard drum for some nice druid thing.  It doesn’t make sense to me to do it that way though.  I’m not a merchant and never want to be one.  On lower level items trading can be a good way to earn some cash or get good items you need.  At the higher levels these types of trades only encourages the item camping and greed. <BR>  <BR> Knowledge is power.  Having level 10 characters in level 50 gear will not kill a dragon.  Having a group of lvl 46-50 characters who trust each other and who know how to play in whatever gear they have will!  Yes I get jealous as heck!  Little Keke is out dressed by many 30 druids on our server (had an aquaintance brag to me last weekend after inspecting my gear how they have more wisdom than me because lvl 50 char X gave them a thingamahoosey cloak.)  Well, guess what?  The friends I have made both within the claw and elsewhere is what makes the game worth playing and is what makes me strong… not 15 more mana for a snare spell!  I’ll get my level 50 gear someday … perhaps the old fashioned way and earning it on my way to level 50.   <BR>  <BR> Please feel free to post countering point.  I’m not saying this is the Claw rule.  This is just the way I would like to see it.  I’ve probably missed a lot of important points and would love to have a debate on this issue.  One thing is certain… we need to decide soon how we are going to handle it.  In the next few weeks there will be more and more rare loots obtained by the Claw members (WAY TO GO!) <BR>  <BR> PS.  Aradan thanks for making me think about this.  I’d love to hear your opinion and thought we should move this discussion to the message board rather than online in guildsay.  You are right, we need to come up with a plan. <BR>  <BR> Keke <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#141419><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub2.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=bramblefoot>Bramblefoot</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif              BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Local user</span><br>   <font color=#7A8798>(1/12/00 8:02 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   I concur</span><hr size=1>  Keke, I totally agree with your philosophy.( and it's not because I'm trying to follow in your footsteps8) Part of what makes us so strong is our devotion to our brothers and sisters. When we take no thought of ourself and put others first, our bonds strengthen. Our trust becomes stronger and as a whole we prosper. <BR>  Some of the most enjoyable times I've had have been in helping others obtain a needed item. I have witnessed the selflessness of others in the guild as they have quested to help guildmates. I would much rather see a coveted item on a Claw, than to sell for profit or personal gain.  <BR>  I, myself have gained the coveted Paw gloves and in my continuing efforts around Paw, my thoughts aren't &quot;now I can sell the next pair I find for xxxpp&quot;, but &quot;Keke will love it when I get a pair of these for her!&quot; <BR>  I don't forsee a problem with the loot issue as the calibre of our membership has proven time and again that we are above such things. I've seen many players join guilds for the sole purpose of benefiting from membership &quot;perks&quot;. The greatest thing we offer one another is not wonderful magic items or loot, but friendship and a wonderful gaming experience. <BR>  I know that if I don't recieve a desired object because it goes to another not to be upset or jealous, because I will obtain it eventually. My friends will see to that. <BR>  <BR> Bramblefoot-still wearing patchwork-Stormfisher <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub2.ezboard.com/uemeraldeyes.showPublicProfile>emeraldeyes</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_greenspot.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>   <font color=#7A8798>(1/13/00 12:25 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Looting Procedures </span><hr size=1> Option #1:  Need before Greed. <BR>  <BR> Has been and always will be my philosophy.  But Keke's post does bring up another question.... <BR>  <BR> Are we doing some of the lower levels harm by simply passing down the items.  I learned a great deal in camping for each of the items I have obtained.  Learned Zone layouts, met great people, learned how to gracefully become part of a camp and how to gracefully leave....each item forced me into first researching about the item on the web and then exploring and learning about the area on EQ.  By simply passing down the items, are we doing damage to the skill development of those that recieve the gift? <BR>  <BR> I will continue to pass on my items to younger claws...I have specifically targeted Trinitti as the heir to my items...but I'd hate to think these gifts may be robbing her of some much needed experience. <BR>  <BR> Please share your thoughts.... <p>EmeraldEyes BrazenHeart
