hat broke us up was one day we were all sitting around after the list was filled and everyone had everything they wanted (that they could use, we didn't have alt characters because we believed it caused greed and distractions)...and we said, &quot;What next?&quot; and then we all said &quot;Well we have everything we want, we're bored!&quot; lol..and we all split off to other servers from there, and I came to Bristlepain..and the rest you know. <BR>  <BR> In any case, when the needs of the players are met before the wants of others, and the others of the group are loyal enough and will sacrifice their time..that group will become extremely powerful, and nearly invincible, not to mention the increase of trust, companionship. and tactical knowledge.  Vander said it right when she said that we twink all our members because it increases our powerbase as a guild.  The same goes for primary characters and needed equip.  Here are a few GREAT examples for those who need some visuals: <BR>  <BR> Example 1 - I have been drooling over a Mithril 2 hander for several months, it will be the last weapon I have before I go to the planes.  By getting the weapon, I increase my power as a paladin and as a group member.  It lets me hit for 21 damage extremely fast, and who's to say that in a nail biter combat, due to the weapon, I am able to strike down or interrupt a caster that was casting Shock of Force on a near death party member, indirectly saving that person's life, XP and time?  What rule was it - Hit Hard and Hit fast. The faster we strike with more damage, the more mana we save, and the more blood we keep in our bodies.  That is just one example, and it goes from there.  Lets say I get the weapon, if I do I will donate my Silvery 2 Handed Axe to the guild, which increases the power of another player, which increases the power of the group they are in and over all increases the power of the guild.  Do you see the domino effect caused just from getting ONE item for ONE person?  Just think if we all did this??  WOW!   <BR>  <BR> Example 2 - Aradan's Drums.  As we all know Bards are a support class, backing up everyone in the group and speeding the recovery of two of the most important things in EQ - Mana and Health, not to mention several other support songs.  I have seen a 50th level Bard at work, and let me tell you something...she was deadly.  Not from raw damage or spell power but because her songs made the group as a whole more powerful.  We recovered health and mana faster, we were faster in combat, and her STR song stacked with Druid and Shaman spells made us melee gods.  Our down time was nearly zilcho. You know how long it took me to med from oom to full?  Nearly 9 minutes without clarity or her song.  At 50th level with her song or clarity I was ready to go in 3 minutes...not to mention fully healed.  I think you all get the point here.   <BR>  <BR> How to determine want from need? <BR>  <BR> Ask yourself these three questions: <BR>  <BR> 1) How will it benefit me as a player? <BR> 2) How will it benefit the groups I am in? <BR> 3) How will it benefit my guild? <BR>  <BR> If you can honestly answer ALL these questions starting with a &quot;Yes!&quot; then it is a need...2 out of 3 doesn't count.  Any less than 3 is a want.  The faster we gather all our needs, the faster we can get to the wants. (Like Mana stones for all the casters! Hehe).   <BR>  <BR> Twinking lower level players - Em made a good point...why go to Guk?  Why go to Sol B? Why go into these hell holes of death and chaos?  Because we need something there, and in going there we learned the tactics of the area and met new folks and made new friends.  One the other hand...I am sorry, I can think of many other more &quot;merciful&quot; places to go if I just needed XP, and when I was younger in level, this was surely the case.  But not now.  Verant's outlook is that your first 20 levels are there for one reason - to learn the game.  What you learn and the friends you make in your first 20 levels will save your life when you get up there in the 30's and beyond.  This game does not really begin until 20th level, hence the surname and melee damage cap.  I could solo all day long when I was 18th-20th, but when I hit about 24th, blue mobs started hitting me faster, for more damage...and the higher you get in levels, the more you will depend on a group. Which is the purpose of this whole game - interaction with other people.  The majority of people in general just can't get along with others, and those that can and band together can quickly become the most powerful people in this game.  This is why support classes are so important. <BR>  <BR> Now back to twinking - Not many people know this, and I am reluctant to let the cat out of the bag...of those that know this, not many believe it but I will tell you it is true.  There is an in-game code that prevents over twinking of characters.  Verant was not stupid - What is this code?  Well I am not going to go into it too much but technically it comes down to this...the code determines the average equip you should have according to level.  Example - 1-5 Cloth, 6-10 leather, 11-15 banded...and so on(just an example I am not sure of the actual coded limits).  This equip cap is removed along with the damage cap at 20th level.  So you may be 5th level with all ruby and you may look really pretty, but technically the server sees you as wearing cloth, and this is why twinked players do no better than those with average equip.   Keep this in mind when looking for items for your alt characters or lower level guild players.   <BR> To me there is a difference - Helping people and twinking people.  I think you get it. :) <BR> I will not twink anyone under 20th level because I know it won't do any good.  Twinking other guild members? Hell yeah, as long as they are above 20th, and no other player in the guild who is higher level NEEDS it..it is theirs. <BR>  <BR> Till about a week ago I was doing all I could to save up money to buy a mithril 2 handed sword, doing blacksmithing and making crafted armor to sell to others but I gave up, because I realized that by not helping my guild mates get what they need, hurts my chances of getting what I need...and I am doing no good for my guild by wasting my time camping something that I am going to use to sell to some other player.  I have spent a ton of cash on CHR gear and gems for these crafted quests..I had 1000 PP last week, and I now have only 21..lol...and guess what?  I don't mind being broke, because I know by giving this crafted armor to my guildmates who need it, takes me one step closer to being a millionaire. :) <BR>  <BR>  <BR> Neal aka Zar <BR>  <BR>  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub2.ezboard.com/uicecrusher.showPublicProfile>icecrusher</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=  http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif  BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Administrator</span><br>   <font color=#7A8798>(1/13/00 1:15 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What I have learned concerning loot...</span><hr size=1> Damn Zarr... You are my hero! Umm, I have nothing to add, everything posted her makes Uber Sense...  <BR>  <BR> /high fives Zarr & Guild <p><b>][<u>CE</u></b> - 40th Barbarian Shaman,
